n personal name <i>Eggius</i> + the suffix <i>-idius</i>). The personal name was widely used in France and the Low Countries, partly through veneration of Saint Gilles de Provence, supposedly a hermit of the 7th century near Arles; he was patron saint of cripples, hence the dedication of Saint Giles Cripplegate in London, though the personal name itself was less common in England than elsewhere in Europe. See also   Gilles  .","Irish: adopted as an Anglicized equivalent of Gaelic <b>Ó Glaisne</b>, a County Louth name based on <i>glas</i> ‘green, blue, gray’.","French: variant of   Gilles  , a cognate of 1 above."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John GYLES II was born about 1410, in Hopton, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Ralph GYLES II, was 32 and his mother, Mrs. Ralph Gell, was 32. He married Elene Kinley about 1428, in Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1471, in Wirksworth, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 62."},"et":{"about 1410–1471":"umbes 1410–1471","1410–1471":"1410–1471","1410–1460":"1410–1460","1430–1508":"1430–1508","–Male":"Surnud","1380–Male":"1380–Surnud","1380–Female":"1380–Surnud","about 1428":"umbes 1428","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","about 1400":"umbes 1400","1460":"1460","1471":"1471","about 1410":"umbes 1410","1508":"1508","1380":"1380","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England","Hopton and Griff-Grange, Derbyshire, England":"Hopton and Griff-Grange, Derbyshire, England","Wirksworth, Derbyshire, England":"Wirksworth, Derbyshire, England","Hopton, Derbyshire, England":"Hopton, Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1410–1471":"noin 1410–1471","1410–1471":"1410–1471","1410–1460":"1410–1460","1430–1508":"1430–1508","–Male":"Kuollut","1380–Male":"1380